events.body:
Authorities in Inner Mongolia have shut down a Christian prayer meeting in a private residence, threatening the landlord with severe penalties for hosting what officials termed &#8220;illegal religious activities,&#8221; according to ChinaAid.

The Jinhao Regional Service Center in Tumote Left Banner, Hohhot, ordered a landlord to immediately evict a Christian tenant who was attending prayer gatherings in the rented property. Officials warned the landlord faced administrative penalties, detention, and potential legal consequences for providing a venue for such meetings.

The tenant was labeled an &#8220;internet-based illegal proselytizer&#8221;—reportedly the first official use of this term—and designated a &#8220;key target for strict crackdown.&#8221; Authorities claimed the believer had &#8220;long used the rental property to organize illegal proselytizing and activities undermining national political security.&#8221;

A joint operation involving the Religious Affairs Bureau and public security officials targeted the residence on April 10, after repeated warnings to the landlord went unheeded. ChinaAid reports that officials explicitly linked the private prayer gatherings to threats against &#8220;national political security.&#8221;

The formal notice cited regulations allowing fines between 20,000 and 200,000 RMB for those providing conditions for unauthorized religious activities. ChinaAid notes this enforcement demonstrates that private residences are no longer considered spaces of personal freedom under China&#8217;s religious management system, with even small prayer meetings subject to forcible government intervention.

Pray for believers facing escalating persecution in private spaces across China.

A pastor in Kyrgyzstan was released from prison on March 25 after the Supreme Court changed his sentence to a fine equivalent to three months&#8217; pay, according to International Christian Concern. The 66-year-old pastor now has up to 30 days to pay the fine before facing deportation.

The pastor leads the now-banned True and Free Reform Seventh-Day Adventist Church, which emerged during the Soviet regime and has no affiliation with Seventh-Day Adventists in the United States. The church did not seek state registration, which is punishable by fine, liquidation, or imprisonment. A Forum18 report from 2024 found many small churches avoid registration because &#8220;many people will not want to identify themselves to the regime as founders of a religious community.&#8221;

In early 2024, National Security Committee secret police arrested the pastor and several church members for involvement in illegal religious activities. While in custody in September, he was moved to the prison&#8217;s medical unit to receive treatment for brain injuries. In a November complaint, he wrote that five officers &#8220;hit me with an iron pipe to force me to confess that I committed crimes.&#8221;

The NSC revoked his Russian passport, and he faces deportation costs. Authorities have not ordered his wife&#8217;s deportation, but she will leave with him.

Pray for this pastor and his wife as they face forced exile from their ministry.
